Diagnosis. General —Dorsum dark, sombre, greenish metallic reflections restricted to pronotum and head (
Fig. 1–4
). Clypeal margin distinctly angulate adjacent to median teeth; length of clypeus greater than that of frons. Pronotal disk with distinct midlongitudinal sulcus (
Fig. 2–3
), posterior portion of disk slightly punctured to smooth (
Fig. 1, 4
); basal (posterior) fossae distinct. Metasternal disk slight punctured, with tenuous midlongitudinal sulcus; cap of anterior metasternal angle simple, not bifurcate; cap followed by a small and shallow fossa. Posterior (ventral) surface of protibiae completely granulorugose. Elytral striae simple, not carinulate. Length. 16–19 mm .

Male —Head horn erect, plate-like, not particularly curved anteriorly or posteriorly; width approaching interocular distance; apex tetra or pentatuberculate (
Fig. 7–9, 11
); if pentatuberculate, central tubercle weakly indicated. Pronotal prominence cleat-like, bilobate, lobes directed anterolaterally and flanked by deep, oval concavities, lateral margin of each concavity with weak tumosity above lateral fossa; width of prominence equal to distance between outer margins of eyes (
Fig. 4
). Apical processes of parameres strong, hook-like (
Fig. 5–6
).

Female —Cephalic carina trituberculate, weakly bowed anteriorly; medial teeth acute (
Fig. 10
). Transverse crest of pronotum truncated medially, followed by weak and shallow depression, summit weakly bitumose (
Fig. 1– 2
).

Intraspecific variation and taxonomic discussion. As described and illustrated by Arnaud ( 2002 a), the holotype of
C. terrali
is a male with a tetratuberculate cephalic carina, with the two central tubercles being upright and taller than the laterals ones (
Fig. 11
). One of the two males examined by us from Cláudia has an equivalent carina (
Fig. 9
). However, the two other males (one from Carlinda and the other from Cláudia) have a pentatuberculate carina with the medial tubercle slightly indicated (
Fig. 7–8
) (the lateral tubercles of the Carlinda specimen [
Fig. 8
] are much more acute than those of the Cláudia specimen [
Fig. 7
]). As the two forms (i.e., the tetra- and pentatuberculate carinae) are sympatric and no other distinction was seen by us, we believe that they are just an intrapopulational variation and are not evidence of the existence of two distinct species.
